{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17517677","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17517677"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:55:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:55:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12825"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12825","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12825"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.83,0.05,0.05,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5268"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112796"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5268","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5268"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12825"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94830"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"98"},{"type":"tags","id":"1453"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"10862"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12240"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14321"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18252"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18603"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41669"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45874"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112796","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112796"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for cardiovascular risk review. He has a three-year history of hypertension and was recently diagnosed with metabolic dysfunction-associated steatotic liver disease. He has no other significant medical history. His only regular medication is perindopril. Over the past six months he has implemented diet and exercise changes with a modest reduction in weight; his BMI is now 31 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E, down from 32 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. He is keen to try another online diet. He has no known family history of cardiovascular disease. He is an ex-smoker who quit five years ago with a 15 pack-year history and does not drink alcohol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Using the Australian cardiovascular disease risk calculator, his estimated five-year cardiovascular disease risk is 7% (intermediate risk). Recent fasting blood tests show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAlanine aminotransferase: 120 U/L (10-50)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAspartate aminotransferase: 90 U/L (10-45)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ETotal cholesterol: 7.1 mmol/L (\u0026lt;5.5)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ETriglycerides: 0.6 mmol/L (0.3-2.0)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHigh-density lipoprotein: 2.39 mmol/L (1.0-2.2)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ELow-density lipoprotein: 5.47 mmol/L (\u0026lt;3.7)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ETotal/high-density lipoprotein ratio: 3.0\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in the management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Continue lifestyle measures only","Discuss statin therapy","Discuss ezetimibe therapy","Discuss proprotein convertase subtilisin/kexin type 9 inhibitor therapy","Discus fibrate therapy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ELipid-lowering therapy for primary prevention in Australia is mainly guided by the absolute cardiovascular disease risk. According to the 2023 Australian guideline for assessing and managing cardiovascular disease risk, for people at intermediate cardiovascular disease risk (estimated five-year risk 5% to \u0026lt;10%), blood pressure-lowering and lipid-modifying pharmacotherapy should be considered after discussing the benefits and harms of treatment, unless contraindicated or clinically inappropriate. This patient has several key considerations for pharmacological therapy: intermediate cardiovascular risk (7%), metabolic dysfunction-associated steatotic liver disease with markedly elevated low-density lipoprotein cholesterol (5.47 mmol/L).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStatin therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first-line pharmacological option. Statins provide the greatest low-density lipoprotein reduction and cardiovascular risk reduction, and are considered safe to initiate in most individuals with chronic liver disease. However, caution is required when it is prescribed for patients with decompensated liver disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinue lifestyle measures only\u003C/strong\u003E could be considered in intermediate-risk patients with mildly elevated lipids, but is insufficient given the persistently high low-density lipoprotein (5.47 mmol/L) despite six months of lifestyle modification. The Australian guideline recommends considering pharmacotherapy in intermediate-risk patients alongside ongoing lifestyle change, particularly with such markedly elevated low-density lipoprotein.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEzetimibe monotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E achieves a smaller reduction in low-density lipoprotein (approximately 15-20%) compared to statins (30-50%) and is usually reserved for statin intolerance or used as add-on therapy when targets are not achieved with a statin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProprotein convertase subtilisin/kexin type 9 inhibitor\u003C/strong\u003E therapy is generally reserved for very high-risk patients or familial hypercholesterolaemia not controlled on maximally tolerated statin plus ezetimibe; it is not first-line in a primary prevention setting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFibrate therapy\u003C/strong\u003E primarily lowers triglycerides and has a limited effect on low-density lipoprotein; this patient\u0027s triglycerides are low (0.6 mmol/L), and the predominant abnormality is elevated low-density lipoprotein.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Statins are appropriate and safe to initiate in most individuals with chronic liver disease.","However, caution is required when it is prescribed for patients with decompensated liver disease."],"references":["Hilmer SN, Shenfield GM, Le Couteur DG. Prescribing in patients with abnormal liver function tests. Aust Fam Physician. 2013;42(1-2):16-19. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2013/january-february/prescribing-in-patients-with-alft","Nelson MR, Banks E, Brown A, Chow CK, Peiris DP, Stocks NP, Davies Ao R, Raffoul N, Kalman L, Bradburn E, Jennings G. 2023 Australian guideline for assessing and managing cardiovascular disease risk. Med J Aust. 2024 May 20;220(9):482-490. Available at: https://www.mja.com.au/journal/2024/220/9/2023-australian-guideline-assessing-and-managing-cardiovascular-disease-risk","Therapeutic Guidelines. Nonalcoholic fatty liver disease. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines; 2020 Dec."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94830"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12825"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94830","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94830"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-06T11:52:07+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-06T11:52:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5268"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112796"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https: